I have only one month left until my AP exams.
I haven’t really studied much at all.
But I have kept memorizing vocabulary every single day, kept learning something little by little, even if it was just a tiny bit.
I have tried, broken down, felt anxious, and blamed myself nonstop.

Other people have five points on ten APs and eight competition awards.
I’m just someone who only entered the game when everyone else’s application materials were almost ready.
On top of that, my grades aren’t even good.
Yeah, that’s true.

But so what?
Everyone starts from a different place.
It took me forever to climb out of my own abyss and reach the ground.
It took me even longer to stand up from the ground.
Right now, I am standing.
Even if I’m shaking unsteadily, I am standing.

Why should I compare myself to people who were already on the track running fast from the beginning?
It’s not fair.
It’s so unfair to me.

Everything I do now, I worry whether I can get into the school I want.
I worry about what others will think of me if I fail.
I worry about letting myself down again.

But so what?
I can still get back up.
I choose to trust my own judgment and recognition of myself.
I believe my potential is strong, and I can outpace others through my hard work from now on.
I also believe my personality and authenticity are what matter most.

Starting today, I won’t think about how to win over the Ivy League anymore.
I don’t need to.
If you don’t accept me, you’re just blind to my worth.

I will try my absolute hardest to prove to myself that I am one of a kind.
I take back the right of anyone to judge me.

Right now, I tell myself: you are fucking awesome.


